# Task: sit

Make the robot sit. A quadruped sit is characterized by:
- Rear legs fold under the body, with rear feet pulled forward and up toward the belly.
- Front legs remain extended, supporting the weight of the shoulders.
- The body tilts back (negative pitch), with the rear of the body lower than the front.
- Base height is lower than standing, but not as low as laying.

# Strategy hints

- Rear foot_z controls how much the rear drops. Less-negative foot_z (closer to zero) pulls the rear up and lowers the body.
- Rear foot_x controls rear leg tuck. More-forward values (closer to 0 or positive) fold the rear legs further under the body.
- Front feet should stay near their home positions to keep the shoulders supported.
- Symmetry: left and right legs should have identical foot targets unless you have a specific reason otherwise.
- The three reward terms (|Δh|, |Δroll|, |Δpitch|) are additive. All three must be small for high reward.

